response.message:
@Tim Post: 
>why not start off every new meta site with these questions already present

We considered that (it may happen, you never know). But there is something to be said for letting the community ask these questions of themselves. There is more a sense of ownership when the community takes it upon themselves to ask (and resolve) these questions... rather than just answering some "form letter" we post as part of a requirement by us.

Hence, the idea of the blog post to urge users to ask these questions of themselves.


@Alex Andronov: I agree. With the proliferation of guest bloggers, we need a better way to identify who is speaking.


@John Ferguson:
> “Prefer non-hyphenated names.” :) 

Ha! I was wondering if anybody would pick up on that.

@Jon

You are right, the community is what makes SO great, and the team has been singing that refrain from the beginning.  But there is a reason, beyond good software, than such an excellent community has gathered at this particular site.  

So don't miss this key point:  Joel and Jeff ran an excellent extended promotional campaign, through their blogs and podcasts.  Robert is making it very clear that the SE team is not able or willing to do the same for each and every SE site . . . but someone has to do it.
